Perhaps a fisheye lens for a nest box is a bit too much.
One learns never to learn.
I should have known better, since I've built one with a "normal" lens before.
I will write more about it on the weekend once I have installed the second one.
Let's just say that the birds will have better internet connectivity than I did in 2015.
At least that's the plan.
The box that already has a nest sucks up a lot of WLAN data.
It will be a bit harder for him to go online with the other one.
Okay, I hung the new nest box today. This is how it looks in its new spot in the garden.
But let's step back a bit. No one asks: "What exactly is inside?"
At the top is one of those ESP32 camera boards with a camera and a fisheye lens and an IR LED from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The reason for the strange shape of this plastic box is the swivel side wall of the nest box. I bought it that way and couldn't change it, so I had to build around it.
Since there is no electricity in the garden, the whole thing is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 battery.
I neither photographed the battery nor the charger, but here is a picture of the panel.
In the gray box hanging at the side of the nest box, the battery is located.
When charged, it provides approximately 4 hours of runtime.
This I call a feature. This way the birds also get some privacy.
At first, I wasn't sure if the internet in our garden would be sufficient for this setup. The access points I replaced last autumn in the fall wouldn't have been enough.
But the new ones cover this area very well.
It's almost a shame because I had planned to install a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and direct it downwards into the garden.
Maybe I will do that if I set up more nest boxes with cameras in the future. Especially in areas that are further away from the house, I will probably need it.
Now the camera is offline and I don't know why. It turned itself off just an hour after sunset.
The battery might not have charged for three hours before sunset because there wasn't enough light.
Or less than half a day was too short to fully charge the battery.
I must wait and see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have telemetry for the battery. I might need to change that in the future.
I think a few more sensors would be a good idea.
And maybe a battery that at least theoretically is capable of keeping the system running overnight.
Ah yes, and another lens.
Fisheye is quite excessive.
But I'm already looking for components on Digikey so I can build my own board specifically for this.
Or not. We'll see.
And it is still offline.
Well done.
According to the actual solar cells on the house, we have only about 90 minutes of proper sunlight.
Let's wait another one or two hours to see what happens – or not.
Still offline.
It's also never easy.
It turned out that on the USB-C breakout board I used to connect the charger, the 5V and GND were swapped on the silkscreen.
I swapped the cables and now the charge indicator lights up.
The ESP did not go online immediately. Let's wait a few minutes.
One hour passed and it is still offline.
It seems like he is rebooting and triggering Tasmota's reset function.
I think the panel is just not suitable. I have ordered a larger one and hope that will work then.
Check out what I found in my workshop.
A 24V panel. Unfortunately, the sun is already so low (and partially blocked by a tree) that the value drops practically to zero as soon as I put the device into operation.
I'll have to wait until tomorrow to see if this panel is sufficient or if I need the better one I ordered.
According to Amazon, I bought the panel in 2021 and it is supposed to deliver 12V at a maximum of 1.2A.
Either something is wrong with the panel or my multimeter, or the data has been changed.
Good news!
You have changed the data, and the ones I have are wrong.
The old and also the new listing title calls it a 12V 10-W panel.
Therefore, I never delete old emails.
Oh look! The thing went online about an hour ago, for about half a minute.
Maybe the panel just managed to charge the battery for 38 seconds of runtime in over two hours.
Guess what: It's cloudy today. Therefore, I'm not sure if the (probably faulty) solar panel will manage to generate enough electricity.
Wait and see.
Update: I have installed the new panel and now it seems to be working.
It might still work once the sun sets, but let's give it a chance.
Fun fact: I use the Ping integration in Home Assistant to see if it is online or not.
The average connection time is 102 ms. Not particularly good, but also not terribly bad.
